 symbolic role across many cultures. In modern contexts, the lion often rep=
resents courage, assertiveness, and leadership. The concept of =E2=80=9Chav=
ing the heart of a lion=E2=80=9D reflects the animal=E2=80=99s association =
with bravery and strength of character.</p><p>In my experience, my lion por=
trait is bought as a =E2=80=98Dad=E2=80=99 gift. Indeed I called it =E2=80=
=98Head of the Family=E2=80=99 to reflect the traditional male role. I must=
 add, that it=E2=80=99s mainly bought tongue-in-cheek and with a heavy dose=
 of irony.</p><p>In popular culture, from heraldry to sports team mascots, =
the lion represents strength, pride, and nobility. There are lion images ev=
erywhere. My lion portrait is often bought to be copied as a tattoo.</p><p>=
The lion is well-represented in religion. Biblical references, such as the =
=E2=80=9CLion of Judah,=E2=80=9D associate the lion with divine power and p=
rophecy. In Hindu tradition, the goddess Durga rides a lion, symbolizing po=
wer and divine protection.</p><p>In ancient Egyptian mythology, the lion-he=
aded goddess Sekhmet embodied both destruction and healing. And let=E2=80=
=99s not forget the Zodiac.</p><p>In Greek mythology, the constellation Leo=
 is tied to the Nemean Lion, a fearsome beast defeated by Hercules as one o=
f his twelve labors. This powerful symbol has carried through to modern ast=
rology, where Leo embodies strength, bravery, and regal authority.</p><p>Co=
nservation efforts have also made the lion a symbol of wild Africa and the =
importance of preserving natural habitats.</p><div style=3D"height:20px" ar=
