re></div><p>I sales terms the popularity of bears is mostly concerned with =
brown bears. That may be related to the shared cultural and historic experi=
ences of Eurasian and North American cultures where brown bears predominate=
.</p><p>Many North American Tribes revere the bear. Once widespread across =
the plains, grizzly bears appear in the legends and folklore of native Amer=
icans and represent wisdom, leadership, and healing.</p><p>Bears are known =
for their fearless ability to carry on fighting when wounded, leading to a =
belief that bears can heal their own wounds. They represent supreme courage=
.</p><p><a href=3D"https://viking.style/viking-bear-symbol-meaning/" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Ancient Norse traditions </a>associ=
ated the bear with the god Odin, representing the warrior spirit. The Vikin=
gs had the concept of =E2=80=98Berserkers=E2=80=99 These were warriors who =
turned into bears in battle.</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://druidry.org/resour=
ces/the-bear" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Celtic lore</a>=
, the bear symbolized power and sovereignty. Modern interpretations often v=
iew the bear as an emblem of introspection and personal power.</p><p> In Ne=
w Age spirituality, the bear is often invoked for grounding, courage, and c=
onnecting with Earth=E2=80=99s energies. The notion of =E2=80=98Mother bear=
s=E2=80=99 arises as fierce protectors of their offspring.</p><p>The bear=
=E2=80=99s ability to stand upright has long fascinated humans, contributin=
g to its symbolism of bridging animal and human realms. Conservation effort=
s have also made the bear an icon of wilderness preservation and respect fo=
r nature.</p><div style=3D"height:20px" aria-hidden=3D"true" class=3D"wp-bl=
