 and power. It has a masculine appeal. In my experience, women are less att=
racted than men, but they buy eagle images for their partners.</p><p>I drew=
 this portrait after multiple requests only to discover that most people wa=
nt an eagle with its wings spread out! You can=E2=80=99t win.</p><p>It=E2=
=80=99s worth noting that eagles are usually depicted as =E2=80=98Bald Eagl=
es=E2=80=99 in commercial art, no doubt because of the emblematic power it =
represent in North America.</p><p>In ancient cultures, from Rome to Native =
American tribes, the eagle was revered as a messenger of the gods and a sym=
bol of divine power. Its ability to fly at great heights has long been asso=
ciated with the spiritual realm.</p><p>In Christian iconography, the eagle =
represents John the Evangelist and divine inspiration.</p><p>Modern interpr=
etations often view the eagle as a symbol of freedom, perspective, and nati=
onal pride, as seen in its use as a national emblem for many countries, inc=
luding the United States.</p><p>In spiritual terms, the eagle is invoked fo=
r its sharp vision, both literal and metaphorical, representing clarity of =
thought and the ability to see the bigger picture.</p><p>Its hunting prowes=
s symbolizes focus and the achievement of goals.</p><div style=3D"height:20=
