ncil Drawin by Kevin Hayler</figcaption></figure></div><p>Mostly a male ico=
n, a stag=E2=80=99s head is the epitome of masculinity. It has a raw testos=
terone-fueled appeal and is widely associated with fertility and sexual ene=
rgy. Just think of stag parties and male excess.</p><p>It was not always so=
 egalitarian.</p><p>The connection between stags and royalty, particularly =
through hunting, dates back centuries and is deeply rooted in European cult=
ure.</p><p>The stag was seen as a noble and elusive animal, symbolizing kin=
gship, honor, and power. Royal hunts, especially for stags, were not just a=
bout sport but also a demonstration of a ruler=E2=80=99s strength and autho=
rity.</p><p>In medieval Europe, the stag hunt was reserved for the nobility=
, reinforcing the idea of social hierarchy. Kings and nobles engaged in the=
se hunts to showcase their prowess, often seen as embodying the virtues of =
leadership.</p><p>The =E2=80=9CHart,=E2=80=9D a mature stag, was especially=
 prized, and hunting one was seen as a mark of royal privilege. This practi=
ce reinforced the stag=E2=80=99s association with regal qualities and domin=
ance.</p><p>In Celtic mythology, the deer is associated with fairy realms a=
nd supernatural beings, often serving as a guide between worlds.</p><p>Many=
 Native American cultures view the deer as a messenger of spiritual wisdom =
and a symbol of sensitivity and intuition.</p><p>In Christian iconography, =
the deer is sometimes associated with piety and devotion.</p><div style=3D"=
