in my life and it=E2=80=99s a thrill every time. Tigers have charisma that =
even lions can=E2=80=99t match. Just hearing the alarm calls of jungle anim=
als as a tiger glides somewhere through the forest is enough to make the ha=
irs on your neck stand up.</p><p>All my encounters were in India and Hindu =
mythology associates the tiger with divine power, often depicted as the mou=
nt of goddess Durga.</p><p>In Chinese culture, the tiger is one of the four=
 sacred animals, representing strength, bravery, and warding off evil spiri=
ts. It is one of the 12 symbols of the Chinese zodiac and those born in the=
 year of the tiger are also competitive, unpredictable, and confident.</p><=
p>Sadly, tigers are so mythologized in China culture for their strength and=
 power, their body parts are used in Chinese medicine in the belief that th=
ese qualities can be passed on to people.</p><p>It;s not just China, many S=
outheast Asian cultures revere the tiger as a symbol of royalty, spiritual =
authority and fierce drive. The =E2=80=98Tiger=E2=80=99 economies are aptly=
 named.</p><p>In modern contexts, the tiger often represents passion, sensu=
ality, and personal power. The phrase =E2=80=9Ctiger mom=E2=80=9D reflects =
the animal=E2=80=99s association with fierce protection and ambition.</p><p=
>Spiritually, the tiger represents courage, assertiveness, and overcoming f=
ears. The tiger=E2=80=99s solitary nature and stealth have also linked it t=
o introspection and the hidden aspects of one=E2=80=99s personality.</p><di=
